    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter April 16 with a primary focus on exploiting platoon advantages to offset a slate of mid-tier opposing arms. **Yordan Alvarez** remains our premier offensive engine, leading the unit with a 65.44 score against Juan Mejia. Despite a park penalty, his elite 0.393 xwOBA and favorable #2 spot in the order make him a locked-in start. **Junior Caminero** also projects as a strong play (59.77) at third base, as his profile holds up well even against the reasonably effective Leasure. While **Gary Sanchez** (58.67) benefits from the handedness advantage against Patrick Corbin, his status remains \"Lineup Pending\"; should he fall out of the #4 hole, his efficiency score is expected to dip significantly.\n\nWe are forced to navigate a thin bench today, with core speed contributors like **Trea Turner**, **Pete Crow-Armstrong**, and **Kyle Schwarber** unavailable due to team off-days, and **Christian Yelich** remaining sidelined on the IL. Consequently, we are leaning on **Dillon Dingler** (55.99) over other fringe options to handle catcher duties. While his score is bolstered by a +14% dynamic platoon boost against Bubic, we are wary of his potential volume risk; the threat of him being held for late-inning defensive or pinch-running situations (a -2% adjustment for his 40% SB potential) keeps his ceiling in check. \n\nThe most precarious position on our roster is currently shortstop, where **Josh Smith** is clinging to a 40.86 efficiency score. A negative 15% platoon adjustment against Jacob Lopez significantly dampens his outlook, and his reliance on a #7 spot in the order leaves him as a \"marginal\" play at best. We will be monitoring the final lineup cards closely; if **Josh Smith** drops lower than projected, we risk burning a daily game cap on a below-floor performance. Until our primary speed threats like **Victor Scott II** or **Caleb Durbin** return to active status, we must be disciplined in our willingness to bench players who do not clear the 40-point threshold.",
